# Build vs. Buy: Own Search Engine or Integrate Algolia?

## Context

**MarktLab** is a B2B marketplace for industrial wholesalers in DACH. Scale-up, 60 developers, €30M ARR, PostgreSQL-based, Next.js web app. Platform hosts 180,000 products from 400 suppliers, averaging 12 attributes per product.

Current search runs on PostgreSQL Full-Text-Search. User feedback: **poor relevance, no faceted filters, slow on complex queries**. Conversion on search results sits at 3.2% — industry benchmark: 8%+.

CPO has tasked Engineering: better search must go live in 6 months.

## Your Role

You are a **Senior Software Engineer** on the Platform team. Your Tech Lead asked you to submit a **Decision Doc**: Do we build search ourselves on Elasticsearch/OpenSearch, or buy Algolia/Typesense? Leadership team decides tomorrow afternoon based on your paper.

## Starting Position

**Team & resources:**
- 2 Senior Engineers (including you) could lead this project
- Additional 0.5 SRE capacity for infrastructure
- Budget: up to €120k in year 1, beyond that needs CFO sign-off

**Candidates:**

| Option | Type | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| Elasticsearch (self-hosted) | Build | Full control, no vendor lock-in | Ops burden, cluster tuning, 3–6 month build |
| Algolia | Buy (SaaS) | Live in 4–6 weeks, top search relevance out-of-box | €24k–€60k/year depending on traffic, vendor lock-in |
| Typesense (self-hosted) | Build-light | Open-source, faster deploy than ES | Less mature, smaller community |
| Pinecone / Weaviate (Vector) | Exotic | Semantic search possible | Overkill for current use case |

**Requirements from PM:**
- Faceted search (brand, price, lead time, category)
- Typo tolerance
- Autocomplete
- Sub-200ms P95 latency
- Admin interface for relevance tuning
- Multilingual (DE, EN — later IT, FR)

**Technical reality at MarktLab:**
- DevOps team is 2 people, currently no capacity for Elasticsearch cluster
- Product data updated 4x daily from supplier feeds (ETL via Airflow)
- No existing message queue; events run via DB polling
- Leadership allergic to "6-month engineering projects" — last internal build took 14 months and was later replaced with SaaS

## Your Task

Deliver a **2-page decision doc**:

1. **Recommendation** (first page, first paragraph — not at the end). Which option, why, in 3 sentences.
2. **Trade-off matrix**: 3 realistic options (cut ones you don''t take seriously) against 5–6 criteria: Time-to-Value, 3-year TCO, Ops Burden, Relevance Quality, Flexibility, Risk.
3. **Cost calculation**: 3-year TCO model (effort + infrastructure + licenses) for your recommended option.
4. **Migration plan** (rough phases, no Jira tickets): How do we get from PostgreSQL-FTS to the new solution without downtime?
5. **Risks & open questions**: What don''t you know yet, and how do you de-risk it?

## Guiding Questions

- What''s the riskiest assumption in your proposal? If it''s wrong, what does it cost?
- Leadership is "allergic" to long build projects. How much does that bias your purely technical recommendation — and is it legitimate?
- Algolia costs maybe €150k over 3 years. Two senior engineers for 6 months cost fully loaded ~€250k. Why do engineers often still think "we''ll build it ourselves"?
- What''s **reversible vs. irreversible** here? If Algolia triples in price in 2 years, how quickly can you exit?
- What would you deliberately *not* do, even if others suggest it (e.g., vector DB for "AI search" because it''s trendy)?

## Match Info

**Fits:** Software Engineer (Backend / Full-stack), Technical Product Manager, DevOps Engineer, Site Reliability Engineer, Data Engineer, Mobile Developer, Technical Account Manager
**Tests primarily:** Architecture Judgment, Business Awareness, Technical Writing, Pragmatism
**Industry fit:** Tech, SaaS, all data-intensive platforms', 50, 'intermediate', '{"Architecture Trade-offs","Cost-Benefit Analysis","Technical Writing","Pragmatism vs. Engineering Ambition"}'),
